I’m not a New Year’s resolution person. I feel it became such a mainstream thing, that’s why I totally resist from doing so around this time of the year;) ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
That being said, I still have an intent to draw and paint more and becoming better at it this coming year. So here is my first watercolor sketch of the year and hopefully not the last.

I‘m back home from Rome. It was a short but a very pleasant trip, everything went so smoothly like never before. I feel like the city became much nicer and cleaner since I went there last time many years ago. Also, to my surprise I haven’t seen many smokers anymore. 
I used to go to Rome quite often when I was living in Europe but I couldn’t stay there for longer than a week. I remember feeling aggravated about Roman traffic and the obnoxious taxi drivers. This time, it didn’t seem nearly as chaotic as before. I guess New York life toughened me up. ;) ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀ ⠀⠀⠀⠀ I‘ve taken tons of photos and videos and will continue to share them on my stories for a while. So if you‘d like to see more, check them out!

That’s a wrap... another year is almost over. 
It was a successful year but not in a conventional sense: I didn’t make more money, nor did I publish a book or have a personal show. I didn’t get that “job of my dreams” or buy a house, none of that sort. ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀ ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀ ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀ ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀ However, I had the great opportunity to travel together with my daughter @artlarasaunders and attend @drjoedispenza’s week-long meditation retreat, went skydiving and started taking self defense classes.

I was able to shed a few of my limiting beliefs and move a step forward towards mental clarity and peace of mind. I’m so grateful for all of that.

This holiday season was particularly quiet and pleasant. I stayed at home and binge watched documentaries 
about art forgeries, while eating all kinds of plant-based goodies;)
I have to admit I got so hooked on these documentaries. I never would have imagined
that some of these fake art objects make it into prestigious auction houses and museums. 
Let me know if you’re interested, I‘ll share some links in my stories.

Whenever you are creating beauty around you, you are restoring your own soul. – Alice Walker

Known as one of the greatest artists of the Renaissance, 𝙇𝙚𝙤𝙣𝙖𝙧𝙙𝙤 𝘿𝙖 𝙑𝙞𝙣𝙘𝙞  remains as one of the most popular historical figures of today. Here are some facts you might find interesting:

𝘿𝙖 𝙑𝙞𝙣𝙘𝙞 𝙞𝙨 𝙣𝙤𝙩 𝙝𝙞𝙨 𝙨𝙪𝙧𝙣𝙖𝙢𝙚:
Leonardo had no surname in the modern sense – “da Vinci” simply means “of Vinci”. Vinci is a city and commune of the Metropolitan City of Florence in the Italian region of Tuscany.

𝙄𝙡𝙡𝙚𝙜𝙞𝙩𝙞𝙢𝙖𝙩𝙚 𝙘𝙝𝙞𝙡𝙙:
Leonardo was born on April 15, 1452 to a fifth-generation notary, Piero, and an unmarried peasant girl named Caterina. 
Being an illegitimate child did not carry the stigma then that it had in other eras. Even ruling families like the Medicis and Borgias had plenty of illegitimate children who held rank and social prominence.

𝙉𝙤𝙩 𝙛𝙤𝙧𝙢𝙖𝙡𝙡𝙮 𝙚𝙙𝙪𝙘𝙖𝙩𝙚𝙙:
Despite being a high-profile Renaissance artist, Da Vinci did not have formal education, just basic instructions in writing and math.
He lacked formal education in Latin and Greek.

𝘼𝙢𝙗𝙞𝙙𝙚𝙭𝙩𝙧𝙤𝙪𝙨:
Leonardo was known to have been able to write with one hand and draw with another at the same time.
He developed a system of writing backwards to note down his important findings and to hide secret messages, decipherable only through a mirror.

𝘽𝙚𝙖𝙩𝙞𝙣𝙜 𝙩𝙝𝙚 𝙢𝙖𝙨𝙩𝙚𝙧:
Leonardo while learning painting from his teacher, Andrea del Verrocchio, was asked to draw a painting of an angel. His drawing was so good that Andrea del Verrocchio decided to never paint again.

𝘼 𝙨𝙩𝙧𝙞𝙘𝙩 𝙫𝙚𝙜𝙚𝙩𝙖𝙧𝙞𝙖𝙣:
Pre-dating the animal rights movement by centuries, Leonardo wrote of his love and respect for animals and often questioned whether humans truly were their superiors. Leonardo reportedly bought caged birds in order to set them free and abstained from eating meat.

𝙉𝙤𝙩𝙤𝙧𝙞𝙤𝙪𝙨𝙡𝙮 𝙨𝙡𝙤𝙬 𝙥𝙖𝙞𝙣𝙩𝙚𝙧:
Leonardo was known for being a slow painter and numerous of his paintings have been left abandoned. He was constantly starting works and neglecting to finish the ones he had already begun. According to Mona Lisa Foundation there are two Mona Lisa versions, one of them has been left incomplete.

Life is like 
arriving late for a movie, 
having to figure out 
what was going on
without bothering everybody 
with a lot of questions, 
and then being unexpectedly 
called away 
before you find out 
how it ends.

Joseph Campbell

My favorite urban places are art studios and libraries, somehow I’m so drawn to their aesthetics and atmosphere.
I took this photo about 20 years ago at my #almamater in St. Petersburg where I used to study art history. 
I haven’t been there for almost 15 years and feel a bit nostalgic. It would be nice to go back to revisit the places where I spent my youth...

You must have a room, 
or a certain hour or so a day, 
where you don’t know what was
in the newspapers that morning, 
you don’t know who your friends are, 
you don’t know what you owe anybody, 
you don’t know what anybody owes to you.

This is a place where you can 
simply experience and bring forth 
what you are and what you might be. 
This is the place of creative incubation. 
At first you may find that nothing happens there. But if you have a sacred place and use it, something eventually will happen. ⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀– Joseph Campbell

Venice has experienced the worst flood since 1966 severely damaged churches, museums, monuments, homes and stores.

Since records began in 1872, that level had never been reached even twice in one year, let alone five times in two weeks.

Next Tuesday is #GivingTuesday, it’s a great opportunity to support people in need. Even if each of us donates just a dollar it would make a huge difference for them.

I shared a few links in the stories and I encourage you to make a donation.

If you can’t donate please help to spread the word by sharing it on your social media. 🙏🏼

Maybe every once in a while we can take a break from doing everything faster and quicker to reflect on who we are and where we are going.
– Joe Plumeri

Just as anyone 
who listens to the muse will hear, 
you can write out of your own 
intention or out of inspiration. 
There is such a thing. 
It comes up and talks. 
And those who have heard deeply 
the rhythms and hymns of the gods, 
can recite those hymns
in such a way that the gods 
will be attracted. – Joseph Campbell

What each must seek in his life 
never was on land or sea. 
It is something out of his own unique potentiality for experience, 
something that never has been 
and never could have been 
experienced by anyone else. ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
– Joseph Campbell
